    <div class="sec-t">About</div>
    <p>Gamla Stan (Old Town) occupies the island of Stadsholmen at the centre of Stockholm, where the city was founded in the 13th century. The district covers approximately 1 square kilometre and contains some of the best-preserved medieval urban fabric in northern Europe. Narrow cobblestone lanes wind between merchant houses dating from the 17th and 18th centuries, their facades painted in ochre, mustard, terracotta, and copper green. The island is connected to the surrounding districts by several bridges and is accessible by metro, bus, and foot.</p>
    <p>At the heart of the district lies Stortorget, Stockholm's oldest square, founded around 1300. The square was the site of the Stockholm Bloodbath in November 1520, when Danish King Christian II ordered the execution of approximately 90 Swedish nobles, clergy, and burghers. The surrounding buildings house the Stockholm Stock Exchange building (now home to the Nobel Prize Museum) and a row of 17th-century merchant dwellings. The Royal Palace (Kungliga Slottet), located at the northern edge of the island, is a separate ticketed attraction operated by the Royal Palaces authority at kungligaslotten.se. Mårten Trotzigs Gränd, at just 90 centimetres wide, is the narrowest street in Stockholm.</p>
    <p>Gamla Stan is a living residential and commercial district. The resident population is approximately 3,000 people. The area contains numerous churches, including the Storkyrkan (Stockholm Cathedral, adjacent to the Royal Palace) and the Riddarholmen Church (Sweden's royal burial church), as well as galleries, restaurants, and shops. Riddarholmen, a small adjacent island connected to Gamla Stan's western edge, is home to the Riddarholmen Church and several government buildings. Last updated: March 2026 · Verified</p>
