    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">Is Gamla Stan free to visit?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">Yes. Gamla Stan is a public urban district and free to walk through at any time. No ticket or booking is required. The streets, squares, and outdoor areas are open 24 hours. Individual attractions within Gamla Stan — such as the Royal Palace (kungligaslotten.se), Nobel Prize Museum (nobelprizemuseum.se), and Riddarholmen Church — have separate admission fees.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">What is Stortorget?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">Stortorget is the main square at the centre of Gamla Stan, founded around 1300. It was the site of the Stockholm Bloodbath in November 1520, when Danish King Christian II ordered the execution of Swedish nobles and clergy. The square is surrounded by colourful 17th and 18th-century merchant houses and is freely accessible.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">How do I get to Gamla Stan by public transport?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">The nearest metro station is Gamla Stan (T-bana lines 13 and 14), located at the southern end of the island. From there it is a short walk to Stortorget. Bus lines 2, 57, and 76 stop at Slottsbacken, adjacent to the Royal Palace on the north side of the island. Plan your route at sl.se.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">Are there ticketed attractions inside Gamla Stan?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">Yes. Several ticketed attractions are located within or adjacent to Gamla Stan: the Royal Palace (kungligaslotten.se — from SEK 220 / approx. €19.00 adults), the Nobel Prize Museum (nobelprizemuseum.se — SEK 160 / approx. €14.00 adults), and the Riddarholmen Church (SEK 65). Always book direct through each venue's official website.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">What is the narrowest street in Gamla Stan?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">Mårten Trotzigs Gränd is the narrowest street in Stockholm, measuring approximately 90 centimetres at its narrowest point. It is a public alley located between Västerlånggatan and Prästgatan in Gamla Stan and is free to walk through.</div>
    </div>
